I was in disagreement with the importance of a responsible economic policy, in terms of national security, on Europe. It is ironic that Jeremy was in disagreement with leaders on issues on which he was in disagreement with previous leaders.
As was made clear in the notice of the meeting of the Nottingham East Labour Party on Friday, “we want meetings to be inclusive and productive”.
During the greater part of the eight years that I have been a Member of the Labour Party in this constituency, that is exactly what the Friday night meetings of the General Committee have been.
Unfortunately, this is not the tone of many meetings and the promise of a “more friendly and compassionate” policy has already been forgotten, if it ever really applied in any way.
It is becoming clearer that the Labour Party is intolerant of differing opinions and that each opinion is judged in terms of whether the party leaders consider it acceptable or not.
This began shortly after Jeremy became leader, when colleagues with whom he had previously shared a political vision started to expect him to change his views radically and to adopt positions with which he had never been in agreement, whether on security or on the EU single market.
Whenever I speak in public, regardless of what I say, there is a barrage of insults on social media demanding my resignation, denouncing the policies of the center, telling me that I should not be in the Labour Party.
I am not the only one who has experienced it.
Indeed, I know that I am luckier than some of my colleagues, since the comments about me tend to be political.
I am amazed by the professionalism and determination of my colleagues who face a daily torrent of sexist or racist insults, but never run away.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is the normalization of insults.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we no longer have that wide range of opinions and, with each motion “of censorship” or each change in the selection rules, the party becomes more narrow.
In the last two years, I have received many advices that recommended me to keep my head down and not to make myself heard too much and that way “I would be fine”.
But I haven't got into politics to do that.
Since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago, as a student, I have been motivated by the neglect of the Thatcher government which left my secondary school in ruins, and I have tried to support improvements in public services for those who need them most, whether as a councillor or as a minister in government.
I have never hidden my political ideas, not even in the last elections.
It is impossible that someone in Nottingham East did not know my political positions and the areas in which I did not agree with the current leaders.
I would say to those who promoted the motion of Friday is that I do not understand these desires to lose time and energy with questions about my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party when the country is going headlong to a Brexit that will affect homes, businesses and public services.
The real message is not for Nottingham Momentum, but for the voters, be they Labour or not: I am proud to serve them and I promise that no threat of withdrawal or opportunistic politics will stop me from acting according to what I believe is best for all of you.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
