“The sea is ours”: a Bolivia without a coastline has the hope that the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
The sailors watch a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings, blue flags wave.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: “The sea is ours by right,
Recovering it is a duty.
In all Bolivia, a land without sea, they still remember vividly the lost coast before Chile in a bloody conflict over the resources that took place in the 19th century, as well as the longing to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
Bolivia may have the greatest hopes in decades, as the International Court of Justice is expected to rule on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision”, said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the International Court of Justice ruling on the sea border dispute with Chile on large screens spread throughout the country, with the hope that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent negotiations, Chile has the obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
