The UN agency based in the Netherlands has no power to adjudicate territory of Chile and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any possible negotiations.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s resolution comes only six months after the final arguments indicates that the case was not complicated, said Chilean expert Paz Zárate.
Bolivia's cause may have been hindered by the last four years.
“The problem of access to the sea has been seized by the current Bolivian administration”, said Zárate.
In addition, he suggested that the bellicose rhetoric of Morales has undermined any residual goodwill between Chile and Bolivia.
Bolivia and Chile will continue talking, but it will be extremely difficult to maintain conversations after this.
The two countries do not exchange ambassadors since 1962.
The former president of Bolivia, Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, rejected the idea that the court's decision would be unusually quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will offer Chile “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and the possibility of “putting an end to 139 years of disputes with mutual benefits”, said.
In addition, Calzadilla denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, used the maritime issue as a political weapon.
