John Edward: the linguistic skills are fundamental for the citizens of the world
The independent schools in Scotland have a long history of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students in all of Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS, for its English acronym), are committed to delivering the highest level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools have as their object to prepare their pupils for further education, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy in the world.
As a sector of education that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages are still a popular and desired subject in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message goes to his head. If you talk to him in his language, the message goes to his heart.”
If you speak to him in his language, it reaches his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and generate trust with people from other countries, you can't depend only on English.
If we take into account the recent results of the exams of this year, we can observe that the languages are in the highest places of the classification tables, being the approval rates of the independent schools the highest.
In total, 68 % of the students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that make up the SCIS, showed that 72 % of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72 % of students studying German, 69 % of students studying French, and 63 % of students studying Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support the teaching of foreign languages because they are a fundamental skill that children and young people will need in the future without a doubt.
In the current situation, it is considered that, as an optional subject, languages are at the same level as the subjects CTIM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the Commission for Employment and Skills in the United Kingdom revealed that, of the reasons given by employers on the difficulties they faced in filling vacancies, 17 % were attributed to the lack of linguistic skills.
Therefore, linguistic competences are becoming more and more indispensable for preparing young people for their future careers.
The opportunities for employment that require language skills are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to this competition, which will last a lifetime.
The fact that you can communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow you to get ahead of the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, the 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in the teaching of languages now is important for children today.
If you know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be better equipped to find a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools, he can choose between several languages taught by specialist teachers.
The independent schools in Scotland dedicate all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children for life and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future holds.
In these times, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages still have an important role to play for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages must be considered “competencies for international communication”.
The independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's necessary to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
