North Korea says there is “no possibility” of unilateral disarmament if it does not have confidence
On Saturday, the Foreign Minister of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened his distrust of the United States and that there was no possibility of his country renouncing its nuclear weapons unilaterally under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho declared before the General Assembly of the international organization that North Korea had adopted “important measures of goodwill” throughout the year, as to stop nuclear tests and missiles, dismantle nuclear test sites and commit to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we have not received any similar response from the United States.”
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence in our national security, and, in those circumstances, there is no possibility of us disarming unilaterally.”
Although Ri repeated the known complaints of North Korea about the United States’ resistance to a “phased” nuclear disarmament formula that rewards the country as it takes steps, his statement is important, as he did not reject a unilateral nuclear disarmament, as North Korea has done in the past.
He made reference to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim committed to working toward denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the Korean War, but the United States has said that North Korea must give up its nuclear weapons before it can be considered to have ended the war.
In addition, Washington has resisted calls to soften international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on nuclear disarmament first and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its goal coercively, even objecting to a termination of the war declaration”, Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of the sanctions deepens our distrust.
Ri did not mention any plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced with a bang and a whimper by the US president at the UN General Assembly a few days ago.
Instead of that, the minister put emphasis on three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, leader of South Korea, in the last five months, and added: “If South Korea had been the interested party in the denuclearization of the peninsula instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he said to the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct the missiles of North Korea toward US soil after Trump, in a suicidal mission, called Kim “rocket man”.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving toward disarmament, but said there was still much to do and that sanctions would have to be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said that there was no deadline for this: “We can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward North Korea for its advances.
However, as the US Secretary of State, Mike Pompeo, informed the Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of the sanctions of the Security Council must continue energetically and without non-compliance until we realize the complete and verifiable denuclearization.”
The Security Council has imposed sanctions unanimously on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut off funding for its ballistic missile and nuclear programs.
Pompeo chatted with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and then commented that he would return to Pyongyang in a month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not good.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that there had been advances, but a few hours later North Korea denounced that its “demands were those of a gangster”.
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea committed to dismantling a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the “appropriate measures.”
He said that Kim had told him that the “measures” that he was looking for were the guarantees of security that Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to sleep enough
Thanks to a new course that is being taught this year at Harvard University, all students are now sleeping more in an attempt to fight against the growing culture of studying all night drinking coffee.
A professor discovered that the students of the number one university in the world do not have any idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
His motivation to start the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl approached and asked me why she just found out about this now, in her last year.”
He said that no one had ever spoken to him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were sleeping only during the week.
The course of one hour includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, it is explained to the participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
After, an icon of the campus with interactive icons animates the participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.”
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as any has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco.
He said that the culture of pride in staying up all night still exists and added that modern technology and the pressure students are under mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and a good quality sleep should be “the secret weapon” of students to fight stress, tiredness and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation makes the brain generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying biochemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the whole campus.
Wait until the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program before joining the competitive institution.
The recommendation of Professor Czeisler is that students think about putting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by the screens of electronic devices and LED, which can alter circadian rhythms, so that they would have problems falling asleep.
