The trade war between the United States and China could benefit Beijing
The first salvos of the trade war between the United States and China were deafening, and although there is still a long way to go for the battle to end, a rupture between the countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, launched the first warning at the beginning of the year by putting tariffs on the main Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant climb occurred this week with new tariffs that affect 200 billion dollars (150 billion pounds sterling) in products, which will tax half of the products that enter the United States from China.
In all cases, Beijing has taken retaliatory measures, applying tariffs of five to ten percent to U.S. products worth $60 billion.
China has committed to equal attacks by the U.S., and it is unlikely that the second largest economy in the world will soon relax.
To retreat would mean to give in to Washington’s demands, but to submit to the United States would be too humiliating for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Even so, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the trade war between the United States and China could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick decision in Washington or Beijing could make the conditions for a sudden collapse of the economy in either country is in fact much more dangerous than what the spectators have recognized so far,” said Abigail Grace, associate fellow at the Center for New American Security.
